Anonymous Sun 15 Apr 2018 20:11:59 No.15191266 Report
Quoted By:
>>15191126
I'd say filler can be something like a joke a character tells or something they do that overall gives more insight to them as an individual. Even if it's something seemingly nonsensical like, "They bump into someone else and drop their books", you can use it as a way to show the readers how the character would react to the situation. Do they get angry? Laugh it off? Does it lead to some tragic memory of a past event?

I don't really mean filler as in "useless padding", because ultimately it SHOULD be relevant to the story, but it doesn't need to necessarily move the plot forward. The whole waterpark chapter in Happiest was technically filler that could have been left out, but I feel like it gave a look at how multiple characters react to different environments (even something like their taste in swimsuits) and showed how their relationship with each other has developed over the story.

Anonymous Sun 15 Apr 2018 20:20:10 No.15191376 Report
Quoted By: >>15191524
>>15191126
-Coughing Fit

the key is not actually writing filler. When your writing filler.

It may sound confusing but trust me it's not. An eye for detail as >>15191134 implied can really help flesh out a scene and help with setting the mood. Making it easy for the reader to understand what is happening when it's in your best interest to present events clearly really helps them settle in to the scene.

When I write to fill a gap that appears before me in the story I develop something, always have something of substance going on, wether it's two characters developing their dynamic, your lead musing on something, or just having your lead drinking in the local surroundings and you describing to us what they see.
So don't actually write filler in the sense your used too where filler is just pointless bullshit thats there to take up dead air in an episode of the latest series of supah fightan ninja pirate glacial pacers ZX088-redemption redeemer in-between overblown fight scenes that make no goddamn sense, always have at least something of substance going on.

And above all, have your characters be an active element in those moments, don't just have shit going on in the background as ultimately the brand of stories around here are primarily driven by the characters.

For example, I had a gap in chapter 5 that I was pondering how to fill inbetween the morning and both characters arriving at the field, and I felt like just skipping them along to the fight would change the tone too fast.
I inserted some character interraction that is kicked off by Teth'ra musing over the markings on Tom's machine. This prompts a reaction out of her that stirs her to start a talk with Tom where we learn how he feels about the upcoming fight, and through that we learn how Teth'ra is reflecting on her own feelings as they're shipped off towards battle.
THAT is how you do "filler"
never write actual filler.
Anonymous

Anonymous Sun 15 Apr 2018 21:46:38 No.15192843 Report
Quoted By: >>15193337

>>15190473
This is how Silver Lining gets written, too. I wrote a much more detailed explanation of my process a decent number of threads ago now, but the jest of it is that I have something resembling an outline for what's happening on a story scale, but not a chapter scale. When I sit down to write, I know where I need to get but not how I'm going to get there. That process does occasionally inform major changes to the overarching story, but mostly in the beginning, and in ways that make the wider plot clearer and more interesting rather than more vague. I usually start with a relatively vague main plot and let it sharpen up over the first two chapters or so. I started Silver Lining with
>Porco Rosso-ish, and probably some coming-of-age shit in the same vein as Turkey Shoot.
I didn't know there was anything interesting about Echo's cargo at all until Whitney mentioned it, but I found the plot quick as fuck once she did. By the end of chapter 3 I had an entire, rather densely developed plot surrounded by volumes of worldbuilding that will probably never even bear mentioning in the story.
Same program for the characters too, more or less. I had an idea for how I wanted them to interact (borrowed pretty directly from Turkey Shoot), and then let whoever they actually were sharpen up over the next few chapters.

It's plenty possible to write without knowing exactly where you're going (some authors/professors explicitly encourage it), but you shouldn't be wandering, you should be trailblazing. You may not know what's going on, but you should have the intent of learning. The benefit of doing things this way (other than if it just suits you better) is characters learn very realistically when you're learning with them.

>>15193337
Don't rely exclusively on your intuition; use your memory too. Set a situation, and then simulate the people in it as closely as you can to real people based on both intuition and your memories of how people act in those situations. Don't be afraid to play fast and loose, and substitute as necessary. For instance, virtually every description of serious injury or reactions to serious injury I make is based on a car wreck I was in a few years back. That's my only experience, so that's what gets used. Just dig up the last time you were in a situation even remotely like the one your characters were in, and try to remember how you and others felt and acted. You might have to extrapolate a bit, but you'll be able to find something useful.

It's not painless for anyone. If you really do hit a corner, start over. If you wind up writing a lot that isn't meaningful, delete it. You do need to have some vague idea of what's going on. For the start of Silver Lining, that vague idea was Anon and Whitney feeling each other out along what both were assuming was a master/apprentice sort of relationship, but really wasn't. Whitney's uncertainty provided the comment about the cargo, which provided the actual plot of the entire story. That's a big jump, but I still knew what the characters assumed about each other to begin with, and what they were trying to do with that first chapter (figure out their place in any of this, how they're supposed to act around each other, etc.) That was really what I was writing about until Whitney mentioned the cargo.

>>15194371
It's difficult to say, but if I had to guess I'd say you're writing yourself into a corner because you're getting ahead of yourself. Seal'd fate is very fast. That's not a bad thing in and of itself, but the faster and leaner a story is, the less likely it is you're going to create a plot thread by accident. Where seal'd fate starts to get strong is at the very end in the room with the mother.

Downward Dog, by comparison, does a much better job of showing as opposed to telling. I know that's not really what we're talking about, but my methodology for writing a story relies on information I get in the process of showing. I would never be able to write something in the style of Seal'd fate and still use that method. Something like Downward Dog, however, I could probably find a way to continue.

That's not to say you should be writing in constant, vivid detail all the time. You definitely shouldn't. My approach is usually to feel out a scene to decide if it's going to be important or not. That's pretty straightforward. I just start writing it, and if it's boring, or, better yet, nothing comes to me, it gets glossed over. If I were writing Seal'd, the story would be comprised in majority by the two first meeting, the tour of the town, and meeting the mother. The rest, like the actual duration of the trip to the seal settlement, would probably have been glossed much as you did.

>but i feel like i cant get into my own that way.
Just as a heads up: you can never read your own story as someone else would. It's just impossible. There's a bunch of reasons why, but you will not be able to remove your own perspective on how things 'should be' versus how they turned out in the finished/released product. The audience can't see the perfect vision that you failed to bring to light; they only see what they get and can only make educated guesses as to what you were truly aiming for.

These.

My point is that a story written that lean probably isn't going to cooperate with an on-the-fly narrative because it doesn't give you as the writer enough information at a time to find a direction. You would really need a plan to write something like that, or at least I don't know how else I'd go about it.

I treat in-the-moment detail like a particle accelerator. I bang characters together at high fractions of the speed of light and hope they break into elementary plot. A long scene like the initial dawn patrol scene is great for me because the characters need to know things about each other, so I have a good reason to fire the accelerator a bunch. Eventually I got the whole cargo thing out of one of the collisions. That method works very well for me, but it's completely reliant on sliding into some pretty drawn-out detail. Since I do that anyway, that works for me. If you don't, you'll have to try something else.

If I was going to tell you to actually change anything about seal'd, I'd say focus on the town tour. I would have liked to actually see that, especially because we could learn a lot about anon since he's nostalgic for that shit. If you really feel like revising, I'd say your best bet would be to play with that. It really isn't necessary though.
